{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Single-loop generator",
      "simpleDefinition": "A basic machine that rotates a single coil of wire through a magnetic field to produce an alternating voltage.",
      "anchor": "A bicycle dynamo spinning to power a light.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it produces a steady DC voltage like a battery; it actually produces a varying AC voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Sine-wave",
      "simpleDefinition": "The smooth, S-shaped curve that represents how alternating current changes in direction and strength over time.",
      "anchor": "The visual 'signature' of AC on a test screen.",
      "misconception": "Believing AC is just 'on and off' rather than a continuous, smooth curve."
    },
    {
      "term": "Frequency",
      "simpleDefinition": "The number of complete cycles the sine-wave makes in one second, measured in Hertz (Hz).",
      "anchor": "UK mains power has a frequency of 50Hz.",
      "misconception": "Confusing frequency with the speed of the electricity itself."
    },
    {
      "term": "Periodic Time",
      "simpleDefinition": "The time, usually in seconds, that it takes for the wave to complete one full cycle.",
      "anchor": "The 'width' of one single wave on a graph.",
      "misconception": "Thinking periodic time and frequency are the same thing; they are actually inverses of each other."
    },
    {
      "term": "Amplitude (Peak Value)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The maximum value reached by the wave, measured from the zero line to the highest point.",
      "anchor": "The 'mountain peak' of the wave.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the peak (from zero) with the peak-to-peak (total height)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Peak-to-Peak Value",
      "simpleDefinition": "The total measurement from the very top of the positive peak to the very bottom of the negative peak.",
      "anchor": "The full 'top-to-bottom' height of the wave.",
      "misconception": "Forgetting that this is exactly double the amplitude/peak value."
    },
    {
      "term": "RMS Value",
      "simpleDefinition": "The 'Root Mean Square' or effective value of AC that does the same amount of work as a DC supply.",
      "anchor": "A 230V socket is measured in RMS, not peak voltage.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the RMS value is the same as the peak voltage; RMS is actually lower (approx. 0.707 of peak)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Average Value",
      "simpleDefinition": "The mathematical average of all the values in half a cycle of the sine-wave.",
      "anchor": "A specific calculation used for rectifiers and electronics.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'average' is the same as 'RMS'; they are different mathematical calculations."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Cutting the magnetic flux",
    "One complete cycle",
    "Effective heating value",
    "Zero-crossing point",
    "Peak-to-peak height"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Confusing RMS with Peak values",
    "Mixing up Frequency and Periodic Time",
    "Assuming AC generation is constant rather than varying by angle",
    "Treating Peak and Peak-to-Peak as interchangeable"
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "AC Generation Principles",
      "objective": "Explain how a single-loop generator produces an alternating EMF through magnetic flux interaction.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To generate alternating current, we use a single-loop generator. This machine consists of a loop of wire rotating within a magnetic field between a North and South pole. As the loop spins, it cuts through lines of magnetic flux. This physical action induces an Electromotive Force (EMF) in the wire, which we measure as voltage.",
        "The amount of EMF produced is not constant; it changes based on the angle of the loop relative to the magnetic field. When the loop moves parallel to the flux lines (at 0 degrees), it cuts no flux, and the induced EMF is zero. This is known as the zero-crossing point. When the loop moves at 90 degrees to the flux, it cuts the maximum amount of flux, reaching its peak voltage.",
        "As the loop continues its 360-degree rotation, it passes the 180-degree point and begins cutting flux in the opposite direction. This reverses the polarity of the EMF, creating the negative half of the cycle. This continuous rotation produces the repeating S-shape we call a sine-wave."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the angle of the loop: when is it 'cutting' the most flux, and when is it just sliding past it?"
    },
    {
      "title": "Sine-Wave Characteristics",
      "objective": "Identify and define the key values that describe an AC sine-wave.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "A sine-wave is defined by specific characteristics that electricians must use precisely. The Amplitude, or Peak Value, is the maximum height the wave reaches from the zero line. If you measure the total distance from the top positive peak to the bottom negative peak, you have the Peak-to-Peak Value, which is exactly double the amplitude.",
        "We also measure the wave's timing. Periodic Time is the duration in seconds that it takes to complete one full cycle. Frequency is the number of these cycles that occur in one second, measured in Hertz (Hz). For example, UK mains power has a frequency of 50Hz, meaning it completes 50 cycles every second.",
        "For practical calculations, we use the RMS Value (Root Mean Square). This is the 'effective' value of AC that performs the same amount of work (or heating) as a DC supply. Most test meters display RMS values. Finally, the Average Value is the mathematical average of all values in half a cycle, which is primarily used in specialized electronic rectifiers."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that RMS is the 'effective' value we use for most real-world equipment ratings, while Peak-to-Peak is the full top-to-bottom height."
    }
  ]
}

